}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "http://www.westlaw.com/Link/Document/FullText?findType=Y&serNum=1943118655&pubNum=708&originatingDoc=Id8f5e03b9c1c11d993e6d35cc61aab4a&refType=RP&fi=co_pp_sp_708_481&originationContext=document&vr=3.0&rs=cblt1.0&transitionType=DocumentItem&contextData=(sc.Search)#co_pp_sp_708_481" }{\fldrslt 
{\f2 \strike0 \ul0 \b0 \sa0 \sb0 \fs20 \cf5 \i0 
318 U.S. at page 115, 63 S.Ct. at page 481.
}}}
{\f2 \strike0 \ul0 \b0 \sa0 \sb200 \fs20 \cf1 \i0 
 We refused to apply it beyond that point. We should follow the same course of reasoning here. Certainly nothing in the tradition or practice of discovery up to the time of these Rules would have suggested that they would authorize such a practice as here proposed.
\par 
}
}
}
{\li0 \f2 \qj \b0 \ri0 \fs20 \cf1 \i0 
{\li0 \f2 \qj \b0 \ri0 \fs20 \cf1 \i0 
{\f2 \strike0 \ul0 \b0 \sa0 \sb0 \fs20 \cf1 \i0 
The question remains as to signed statements or those written by witnesses. Such statements are not evidence for the defendant. 
}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "http://www.westlaw.com/Link/Document/FullText?findType=Y&serNum=1943118655&pubNum=708&originatingDoc=Id8f5e03b9c1c11d993e6d35cc61aab4a&refType=RP&originationContext=document&vr=3.0&rs=cblt1.0&transitionType=DocumentItem&contextData=(sc.Search)" }{\fldrslt 
{\f2 \strike0 \ul0 \b0 \sa0 \sb0 \fs20 \cf5 \i0 
Palmer v. Hoffman, 318 U.S. 109, 63 S.Ct. 477.
}}}
{\f2 \strike0 \ul0 \b0 \sa0 \sb0 \fs20 \cf1 \i0 
 Nor should I think they ordinarily could be evidence for the plaintiff. But such a statement might be useful for impeachment of the witness who signed it, if he is called and if he departs from the statement. There might be circumstances, too, where impossibility or difficulty of access to the witness or his refusal to respond to requests for information or other facts would show that the interests of justice require that such statements be made available. Production of such statements are governed by 
}
